.TH UPNPLS 1 "2026-04-07" "upnpls 1.0" "terminal UPnP browser"
.SH NAME
upnpls \- terminal UPnP browser
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B upnpls
.RI [ OPTIONS ] " " [ COMMAND ]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
upnpls is a POSIX shell script that scans for UPnP servers and renderers
and provides a simple menu interface to list containers and items.

The project was developed to explore POSIX sh and awk. It was developed on
NetBSD 10 and tested on Debian (Raspberry Pi) and on WSL1 and WSL2 Debian.

The main goal is to browse ContentDirectory devices and extract lists.
There is minimal support for sending an item's URL to a renderer. This
tool is intended as a utility rather than a full UPnP control point and
is not fully compatible with all UPnP control point features.

There is support for browsing pictures, but due to UPnP limitations only
the first resolution is supported. I tested it with three UPnP servers
and it worked on all of them. It is still possible to obtain the full
metadata list, which contains all available information and resolutions.

The script requires the following external programs: curl, socat,
and xmllint (with xpath support). WSL1/2 does not require socat.

Certain systems and virtual systems may not be compatible with 
socat. Hardware or virtual interfaces who are in your LAN and not
NAT to the host system have a good chance to work.

Output may be formatted in several ways. Options and commands may be
freely mixed. If an option is specified more than once, the getopt-style
option takes precedence.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-s
Show available UPnP devices. If no devices are buffered, a scan is
performed. The device buffer is valid until midnight.
.TP
.B \-S
Same as \-s but forces a scan. Useful when a device was just powered on.
.TP
.B \-l " menu-path"
Display the menu for the specified menu-path or select an item. The path
syntax begins with a dot. The path `.` is equivalent to `-s` but shows only
ContentDirectory servers. In the menu, containers are marked with a `•`
and items with a `»`.

Examples:
.RS
.nf
.1.1  •  Browse Folders
.1.2  •  Music
.1.3  •  Pictures
.1.4  •  Video
.fi
.RE

.RS
.nf
.1.2.52.1  »  Raga Bilaskhani Todi Vilambit
.1.2.52.2  »  Raga Bilaskhani Todi Drut
.1.2.52.3  »  Raga Bilaskhani Tarana
.fi
.RE

.RS                            
.nf
The path `.1.2.52.1` means: 1st server device, 2nd category, 52nd album,
1st song.
.fi
.RE

.RS
.nf
You can invoke the menu as either:

$ upnpls -l .3
$ upnpls .3


If both forms are provided (for example, `-l .3` and `.3`), the `-l`
option is preferred.
.fi
.RE


.RS
.nf
A simple range pattern is supported:

$ upnpls .1.2.3:2-7   lists items 2 through 7
$ upnpls .1.2.3:2,4,7 lists items 2, 4 and 7

Mixed ranges and lists (for example `.1.2.3:2-4,6,9`) are not supported.
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B \-o target
Define the output target and control output format. The argument *target*
may be a renderer selection or an output format specifier.

Examples:
.RS
.nf
$ upnpls -l .3.2.1 -o .1
$ upnpls .3.2.1@.1
$ upnpls -l .3.2.1 @.1
$ upnpls -o .3 .3.2.1


The examples above send the audio/video stream from `.3.2.1` to renderer
`.1`. `-o .` or `@.` lists all available renderer devices.
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B \-v
Some output becomes different/verbose.
.RS
.nf
$ upnpls -vs  prints device details eg. ControlURL's
$ upnpls -vl .1.2.3 prints the real path on top and bottom of the menus.
$ upnpls -v .1.2.3@f=meta prints single-decoded XML

.fi
.RE

.SH "RENDERER COMMANDS"
Renderer commands use the renderer id followed by an equals sign and a
command:
.TP
.B .3=stop
Stops the current stream.
.TP
.B .3=start
Starts a stopped or paused stream.
.TP
.B .3=pause
Pauses the current stream.
.TP
.B .3=?%
Show current volume.
.TP
.B .3=80%
Set volume to 80% (valid range: 0–100).
.SH "OUTPUT FILTERS"
Instead of a renderer you may use a filter:
.RS
.nf
$ upnpls -l .1.2.3 -o f=url
$ upnpls .1.2.3@f=url
.fi
.RE

This prints the streaming URL of the item to stdout.

Currently available filters:
.TP
.B f=url
Prints the URL(s).
.TP
.B f=list
Prints a list with `|` as delimiter. Format:
.RS
.nf
Title|duration|URL|dev-path|internal|internal

Duration may be `-1` if there is no duration.
dev-path is the internal server ID. Every server
uses its own ID syntax. Use it if you build a script
that connects the server directly. 
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B f=meta
Prints the DIDL-Lite HTML-encoded meta XML. The output is double-encoded;
decode it once to obtain readable XML. If titles contain encoded
characters (for example `&amp;`), decode the title a second time.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B upnpls -s
List available UPnP devices (use `-S` to force a scan).
.TP
.B upnpls -l .3.2.1 -o .1=50%
Play item `.3.2.1` on renderer `.1` with volume 50% (same as
`upnpls .3.2.1@.1=50%`).
.TP
.B upnpls -l .3.2.1:4-7 -o f=url
List the URLs of items 4–7 (same as `upnpls .3.2.1:4-7@f=url`).
.TP
.B upnpls .3.2.1.1@f=url | mpv --quiet --volume=50 --playlist=-
Pipe the URL to mpv.
.TP
.B upnpls .3.2.1.1@f=url | xargs curl -s | feh -
Display the picture with the feh image viewer.
.TP
.nf
.B
upnpls .3.2.1:3-8@f=list | awk -F"|" 'BEGIN{printf "%s\\n","#EXTM3U"}{printf "#EXTINF:%s,%s\\n%s\\n", $2, $1,$3}'
.fi
Create an M3U playlist for items 3–8 in menu-path `3.2.1`.
.TP
.B upnpls .1.2.3@f=meta | recode html..utf8 | xmllint --format -
Decode the DIDL-Lite metadata into readable XML. If titles contain encoded
characters they may require a second decoding.
.SH FILES
.TP
.B $HOME/.upnplsrc/
Directory containing the scan buffer file `upnpdevices-YYYYMMDD`. Leave the 
buffer file alone. Every scan will overwrite it.
.TP
.B $HOME/.upnplsrc/config
A simple configuration file used to sort devices because the scan order
can be random. To fix device ordering, add a line such as:
.RS
.nf
deviceorder="MyUPnPServer|MyUPnPSpeakers1|MyUPnPSpeakers2"

Devices not listed will appear at the end of the list.
.fi
.RE

.TP
.B $HOME/.upnplsrc/lib/wsl_scan.ps1
Needed only when using WSL. Neither WSL1 nor WSL2 provide a real network
device for socat, so wsl_scan.ps1 is used instead of socat. upnpls detects
WSL and uses wsl_scan.ps1 when appropriate. The script contains PowerShell
and will not run on Linux or BSD.
.SH BUGS
Keep or fix them. It is just sh.
